<cell id="cell-2"># One-example smoke test — ragas under the hood.
from solution import evaluate

q = "What scaling law governs compute-optimal LLM training?"
a = ("Chinchilla scaling laws show that for a fixed compute budget, model size "
     "and training tokens should scale equally. A 70B model trained on 1.4T tokens "
     "matches a 280B model trained on 300B tokens.")
ctx = ["Training Compute-Optimal Large Language Models (Chinchilla). We find that "
       "for compute-optimal training, model size and number of training tokens should "
       "be scaled equally: for every doubling of model size the number of training "
       "tokens should also be doubled."]
gt = "Chinchilla: model size and training tokens should scale equally with compute."
print(evaluate([q], [a], [ctx], [gt]).as_dict())
# faithfulness ~1.0, answer_relevance ~0.85, context_precision ~1.0, context_recall ~1.0</cell id="cell-2">
<cell id="cell-3"># The pathological case — faithfulness=1.0 but answer_relevance crashes.
# Every claim is grounded in context; the answer addresses the wrong question.
a_off_topic = ("Chinchilla was trained on the MassiveText dataset. The model uses a "
               "Transformer architecture.")
print(evaluate([q], [a_off_topic], [ctx], [gt]).as_dict())
# faithfulness ~1.0, answer_relevance ~0.3 — this is why one metric is not enough.</cell id="cell-3">
<cell id="cell-4"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Under the hood — faithfulness
Ragas's `Faithfulness` metric is (1) split the answer into atomic claims with an LLM,
(2) NLI each claim against the joined retrieved context, (3) return supported/total.
The teaching helper below shows the same math in ~15 lines. Use it to debug low
faithfulness scores — print the per-claim verdicts to see which claim ragas flagged.</cell id="cell-4">
<cell id="cell-5">from solution import demo_faithfulness
score = demo_faithfulness(a, ctx)
print(f"demo_faithfulness = {score:.3f}")
# Matches ragas.Faithfulness within ~0.1 — ragas uses a more detailed claim-split prompt.</cell id="cell-5">
<cell id="cell-6"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Under the hood — context precision
Ragas's `LLMContextPrecisionWithReference` judges each retrieved chunk for relevance,
then computes weighted precision@k over the rank order: a relevant chunk at rank 1
scores higher than one at rank 10. The teaching helper is the same formula.</cell id="cell-6">
<cell id="cell-7">from solution import demo_context_precision
score = demo_context_precision(q, ctx)
print(f"demo_context_precision = {score:.3f}")</cell id="cell-7">
